04506nam a22006135i 9780520962132DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015018713  a97805209621327 a10.1525/97805209621322doi  a(DE-B1597)521125  a(OCoLC)928892298  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aGT2853.U5bD86 2015 4aGT2853.U5bD86 2016 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a394.1209732231 aDuPuis, E. Melanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDangerous Digestion :bThe Politics of American Dietary Advice /cE. Melanie DuPuis. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v5800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Freedom -- t1. Free and Orderly Bodies -- t2. Diet and the Romance of Reform -- t3. Gut Wars: GILDED AGE STRUGGLES AGAINST PURITY -- t4. Pure Food and the Progressive Body -- tPART II. Ferment -- t5. Good Food, Bad Romance -- t6. The Trouble with Purity -- t7. Ferment: AN ECOLOGY OF THE BODY -- t8. Toward a Fermentive Politics -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX -- tCALIFORNIA STUDIES IN FOOD AND CULTURE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout American history, ingestion (eating) has functioned as a metaphor for interpreting and imagining this society and its political systems. Discussions of American freedom itself are pervaded with ingestive metaphors of choice (what to put in) and control (what to keep out). From the country’s founders to the abolitionists to the social activists of today, those seeking to form and reform American society have cast their social-change goals in ingestive terms of choice and control. But they have realized their metaphors in concrete terms as well, purveying specific advice to the public about what to eat or not. These conversations about “social change as eating” reflect American ideals of freedom, purity, and virtue. Drawing on social and political history as well as the history of science and popular culture, Dangerous Digestion examines how American ideas about dietary reform mirror broader thinking about social reform. Inspired by new scientific studies of the human body as a metabiome—a collaboration of species rather than an isolated, intact, protected, and bounded individual—E. Melanie DuPuis invokes a new metaphor—digestion—to reimagine the American body politic, opening social transformations to ideas of mixing, fermentation, and collaboration. In doing so, the author explores how social activists can rethink politics as inclusive processes that involve the inherently risky mixing of cultures, standpoints, and ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDietxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aDietxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aDietxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aDietxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aFood habitsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFood habitszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096213240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962132423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962132/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles